                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d862">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 EW/8–1044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-10T20:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 10, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 10—5:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6429. From Pell. Hurst, Chairman War Crimes Commission, inquired if press
                    statement in despatch No. 17295 satisfactory to Department. Hurst deeply
                    concerned about articles appearing in British newspapers. He has stated that
                    unless contrary advice is received from Department, he will assume that the
                    press statement meets with its approval and accordingly will call press
                    conference next week and release statement. Please instruct. [Pell.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
